\section{Method} 
\subsection{Data Collection}
\subsubsection{Trait selection}
We selected traits based on three hypotheses proposed to explain the evolution of masting. For the predator satiation hypothesis, we selected traits associated with seed attractiveness to predators and the potential for surviving in seed caches, including seed weight, fruit size, oil content, dispersal mode and seed dormancy. For the pollination coupling hypothesis, we aimed for traits related to higher pollination efficiency: pollination mode and reproductive type. For resource matching hypothesis, we included traits responsible for higher flexibility in resource use under varying environmental conditions.
\subsubsection{Data scraping}
For our analyses, we obtained the full species list from the two volumes of \textit{Silvics of North America} \cite{burns1990silvics,burns1990silvics2} (hereafter referred as \textit{Silvics}). We extracted masting data primarily from \textit{Silvics}, using MASTREE as a supplementary source when there was no description on the seed production patterns in \textit{Silvics}. Pollination mode and seed dispersal data were also obtained mainly from \textit{Silvics}. We obtained seed weight data from the Seed Information Database by the Society for Ecological Restoration; gathered seed dormancy data from \textit{Seeds} by Baskin and Baskin and accessed the leaf longevity and oil content data through the TRY database. We compiled fruit size and drought tolerance data from multiple sources, including: \textit{Silvics}, the USDA Fire Effects Information System, the USA National Phenology Network, and The Gymnosperm Database.

We defined masting based on qualitative descriptions of seed production patterns. Although recent studies emphasize quantitative definitions of masting, such data were unavailable from \textit{Silvics}. Instead, we classified species according to key phrases describing their seed production patterns. Species described as producing "a good crop almost every year" were classified as weak masting species, whereas species described as producing "a good crop every several years" or having "irregular seed production" were classified as strong masting species.

We adjusted the data on traits related to masting hypotheses to facilitate easier statistical analysis. For numerical traits with a range (seed weight and fruit size), we recorded the full range from the source, and took the mean value for further analyses. For categorical traits (pollination mode, reproductive type and dispersal mode), we grouped them into broader categories, For example, we classified pollination mode into wind, animal (bird, bat, or insect), or both. The complete raw and processed datasets are available through KNB.

\subsection{Statistical Analysis}
\subsubsection{Masting pattern and single trait}
To analyze the relationship between masting pattern and individual traits, we used \texttt{phyloglm} function in the \texttt{phylolm} package (v. 2.6.2), treating masting as a binary response variable. To construct the phylogenetic tree, we verified all species names using the  \texttt{WorldFlora} package (v. 1.14-5) and updated all species names according to WCVP Backbone data (2025). We then constructed an ultrametric phylogenetic tree in R using the \texttt{phytools} (v. 2.4-4) and \texttt{ape} (v. 5.7-1) packages. We calculated the half-life using the equation $(\log(2)/\alpha)$ and compared it with the tree height (standardized to 1). This metric represents the time required for the influence of ancestral states to decrease by half.
\subsubsection{Masting pattern with a multivariate analysis}
To conduct a multivariate analysis for our categorical traits, we selected non-metric multidimensional scaling (NMDS) with the \texttt{metaMDS} function in the \texttt{vegan} (v. 2.7-1) package and evaluated both two- and three-dimendional solutions \(k = 2, 3\) and selected \(k = 3\) based on the lower stress score. To check for potential patterns, we plotted trait distributions on two panels (NMDS1 vs.\ NMDS2 and NMDS2 vs.\ NMDS3).
\subsubsection{Phylogenetic signal for individual traits}
To check for the phylogenetic signal for our traits, we used different metrics for different trait types. For binary traits, we calculated Fritz and Purvis' D-statistics using the function \texttt{phylo.d} in the \texttt{caper}  (v. 1.0.4) package. For continuous traits, we calculated Pagel's $\lambda$ using the function \texttt{phylosig} in the \texttt{phytools} (v. 2.4-4) package. For categorical traits, we estimated the Pagel's $\lambda$ using the function \texttt{fitDiscrete} in the \texttt{geiger} (v. 2.0.11) package.
