\label{fig:seedweight}
\end{figure}

\section{Results}
\subsubsection{Structure of Data}
In total, our dataset included 188 species, comprising 124 angiosperm species and 64 gymnosperm species. Among angiosperms, \Sexpr{gsub("%", "\\\\%", angio_sum)} of species had masting data available, with strong masting and weak masting species occurring in approximately equal proportions \Sexpr{gsub("%", "\\\\%", angio_mast)}. Among gymnosperms, \Sexpr{gsub("%", "\\\\%", gymno_sum)} of species had masting data available, and nearly all were classified as strong masting species \Sexpr{gsub("%", "\\\\%", gymno_mast)}.
We were not able to get complete trait data for every single trait for all species with masting data. The traits with the greatest amount of missing data were oil content and leaf longevity (Fig. \ref{fig:rawangio} and Fig. \ref{fig:rawcon}).
\subsubsection{Results for Each Hypothesis}
We found relationships between traits related to predator satiation and pollination efficiency and strong masting for angiosperm species. Among the traits related to predator satiation, seed weight was the only traits significantly related to masting (p-value = 0.01, Table \ref{tab:regressionangio}). Larger seed weight was associated with a greater probability of strong masting (Figure \ref{fig:rawangio}). For angiosperms only, increasing seed weight threefold (from a median seed weight of 90.9g to 272.7g) increased the predicted likelihood of strong masting from 0.45 to 0.51 (Figure \ref{fig:seedweight}). The effect was stronger among species with biotically dispersed seeds, where increasing seed weight threefold (from a median seed weight of 1087.15g to 3261.45g) increased the predicted likelihood of strong masting from 0.72 to 0.80 (Table \ref{tab:regressionseed}; Figure \ref{fig:seedweight}).

Among traits related to pollination efficiency, pollination mode was the only pollination-related trait significantly associated with masting (p-value = 0.01, Table \ref{tab:regressionangio}) for angiosperm. Wind-pollinated species had a predicted likelihood of strong masting of 0.62, compared with 0.2 for animal-pollinated species. All gymnosperm species in our dataset were wind-pollinated, and gymnosperms contained a much higher proportion of strong masting species overall.
\subsubsection{Multivariate analysis}
Strong and weak masting species were not clearly separated along any axis in the NMDS analysis. We found no evidence that combinations of traits associated with any of the three hypotheses exlained variation in masting pattern.
\subsubsection{Phylogenetic signal}
Masting pattern showed a moderate phylogenetic signal in both gymnosperms (D = 0.51) and angiosperms (D = 0.58) (Table \ref{tab:dstat}).

Seed weight has strong phylogenetic signal for both angiosperm ($\lambda$ = 0.95) and gymnosperm ($\lambda$ = 0.97). This pattern is also evident in Fig. \ref{fig:coneptangio}. Dispersal mode, leaf longevity, pollination mode and reproductive type also showed high phylogenetic signal in Table \ref{tab:lambda}. However, these values should be interpreted cautiously because Pagel's $\lambda$ is estimated differently for categorical and continuous traits, making direct comparisons inappropriate.

